
Aim

To identify the key classes required for designing the Class Diagram of the Predictive Stock Management System.

Definition of Class

A class represents a real-world entity that encapsulates attributes (data) and methods (operations) related to the system.

Identified Key Classes
1. User

Description: Represents system users.

Key Attributes:

userId

username

password

role

Key Methods:

login()

logout()

changePassword()

2. Admin

Description: Manages system configuration and users.

Key Attributes:

adminId

Key Methods:

manageUsers()

manageSuppliers()

generateAdminReport()

3. StoreManager

Description: Oversees inventory and stock decisions.

Key Attributes:

managerId

Key Methods:

viewStock()

placeRestockOrder()

viewPredictions()

4. InventoryStaff

Description: Handles daily inventory operations.

Key Attributes:

staffId

Key Methods:

updateInventory()

recordSales()

5. Product

Description: Represents items stored in inventory.

Key Attributes:

productId

productName

category

unitPrice

Key Methods:

updateProductDetails()

6. Inventory

Description: Maintains stock information.

Key Attributes:

inventoryId

quantityAvailable

reorderLevel

Key Methods:

updateStock()

checkStockLevel()

7. SalesData

Description: Stores historical sales information.

Key Attributes:

salesId

saleDate

quantitySold

Key Methods:

addSalesRecord()

getSalesHistory()

8. PredictionModel

Description: Performs demand forecasting.

Key Attributes:

modelId

accuracy

Key Methods:

analyzeSalesData()

predictDemand()

9. Supplier

Description: Represents product suppliers.

Key Attributes:

supplierId

supplierName

contactDetails

Key Methods:

supplyProduct()

10. RestockOrder

Description: Handles inventory replenishment.

Key Attributes:

orderId

orderDate

orderQuantity

orderStatus

Key Methods:

createOrder()

updateOrderStatus()

11. Report

Description: Generates system reports.

Key Attributes:

reportId

reportType

generatedDate

Key Methods:

generateReport()

exportReport()

Class Summary Table
Class Name	Responsibility
User	User authentication
Admin	System administration
StoreManager	Inventory decisions
InventoryStaff	Stock operations
Product	Product details
Inventory	Stock management
SalesData	Sales records
PredictionModel	Demand prediction
Supplier	Stock supply
RestockOrder	Inventory replenishment
Report	Reporting
Result

Key classes required for the Class Diagram were successfully identified.

Conclusion

Identifying appropriate classes ensures a well-structured object-oriented design. The Predictive Stock Management System was modeled using clearly defined and relevant classes.
